Defendant Jermain R Palmer in court with attorney Mark A. Pecora.  Tyrone Martin St Junior for James C. Griffin appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy Court Clerk: dds.

Sentencing proceeded.  Statements made by State, defense, and defendant. 
 
AS TO COUNTS 3 AND 4:  The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 3 YEARS ON EACH COUNT, CONSECUTIVE to each other and with any other time being served with credit for 5 days. The INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 18 MONTHS.  The MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION IS 18 MONTHS.  The Court has no objection to probation being served in IL under Interstate compact.

The defendant IS NOT eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program or the Substance Abuse Program.  

The Court STAYED these sentences and placed the defendant on probation for a period of 2 1/2 YEARS with the following conditions.

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION/EXTENDED SUPERVISION:
*Serve 6 months in the House of Correction with release for employment- STAYED until 11-14-14 at 3pm.  No good time. No electronic monitoring.  The Court has no objection to time being served in the state of IL if accepted;
*Obtain AODA assessment and if necessary complete follow-up care/treatment;
*Cooperate with random urine screens;
*No illegal drug dealing or association with drug community (drug users/dealers/houses);
*Cooperate with all rules set forth by the probation agent;
*No new law violations rising to the level of probable cause;
*Participate in Cognitive Thinking;
*Obtain/maintain full time employment or full time school with part time employment;
*Pay all supervision fees;
*Provide DNA sample if not previously done so- pay surcharge;
*Pay all applicable mandatory surcharges, fees, assessments, and costs by the end of probation period- any remaining balance to convert to civil judgment;

The Court finds the state in compliance with victim rights legislation.  The Court ordered restitution set at zero.  If revoked, the Court ordered all financial obligations to be paid through collection of sums by the Department of Corrections from 25% of prison funds and as a condition of extended supervision.  Any remaining balance to convert to civil judgment.  Defendant is informed he may not possess and/or own any firearms.  Defendant is informed he may not vote in any election until his civil rights have been reinstated.  Appeal rights given by the Court. 
Filed;
